sql:
SELECT AVG(average_rating) AS Average_Rating
FROM films
WHERE production_company = 'Your_Production_Company_Name';

SELECT AVG(average_rating) AS avg_rating_after_2000
FROM films
WHERE start_year > 2000;

external_knowledge:
;
Above-average ratings refer to film ratings higher than the mean rating across all films.
;
Genres with more well-rated films indicate a higher likelihood of quality content within that genre.

- 'funny flicks' refers to films in the genre of 'Comedy';
- 'unique individuals' means each person is counted only once, so duplicate user IDs are not considered;
- 'entertained' implies that the individuals have watched at least one of these films.

sql:
SELECT primary_title, average_rating
FROM films
WHERE num_votes > 10000;

SELECT film_id, COUNT(*) AS award_count
FROM film_awards
GROUP BY film_id;

external_knowledge:
- 'Beacon of approval' metaphorically refers to the average_rating calculated by averaging the user ratings; 
- 'Cinematic works' refers to the films produced by the 'Specific Production Company Name';
- 'Nurturing wings' metaphorically implies the production company's role in making the films.

